Wash and dry all produce. Bring @water{3/4%cup} and a @salt{pinch} to a boil in a
small #pot{}. Peel, halve, and mince @shallot{}. Cut @lime{1} in half. Finely
chop @cilantro{}. Drain @pineapple{}, reserving juice, and finely chop flesh.

Once water is boiling, add @jasmine rice{1%cup} to #pot. Cover, lower heat, and
reduce to a simmer. Cook until tender, ~eggs{15-20%minutes}. Remove from heat
and keep covered until meal is ready.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine pineapple, @shallot{2%tsp}, half the cilantro, and
juice from one lime half. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Season
@pork chops{2} all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Add to pan and cook until
it almost reaches desired doneness, ~pork chops{4-5%minutes} per side. Stir in
remaining shallot, @honey{2%tbsp}, pineapple juice, and @water{2%tbsp}. Cook
until pork is done, another ~pork chops{1-2%minutes}. Remove from heat and
stir in a squeeze of lime.

Transfer pork and glaze to a #plate{}; cover with #foil{} to keep warm. Wipe
out pan, then heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in it over medium-high heat. Add
@green beans{1%lb}. Cook, tossing occasionally, until tender but still slightly
crisp, ~green beans{3-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> Add a splash of water to the pan if you're having trouble getting the green
> beans to soften.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}, then stir in remaining cilantro and a squeeze of
lime. Divide between plates, then top with green beans and pork. Drizzle glaze
over pork and top with @pineapple salsa{}.